, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlestead, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Anjou, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Anjou, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Spencer was born in 1310, in Nettlestead, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Robert de Ros. She died in 1415, at the age of 105."},"et":{"1310–1415":"1310–1415","1310–1392":"1310–1392","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1415":"1415","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1392":"1392","Helmsley, Yorkshire, England":"Helmsley, Yorkshire, England","Helmsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Helmsley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nettlestead, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlestead, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Rivenhall, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Anjou, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Anjou, Isère, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1310–1415":"1310–1415","1310–1392":"1310–1392","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1392":"1392","Helmsley, Yorkshire, England":"Helmsley, Yorkshire, England","Helmsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Helmsley, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nettlestead, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlestead, Suffolk,